{"/service/ndnp/tu/batch_tu_dinah_ver01/data/sn98069867/00415621723/1920102301/0393.xml":{"full_text":"T\nSATURDAY, OCTOBER 4S, 1m\nTHE NEWS SCIMITAR.\nPAGE NINE,\nUBS ASKED\n0 CLOSE DO\nBY GOV: PARKER\nLouisiana Executive to Ask\nOther Governors to Have\nCotton Plants Shut Down\nt for Thirty-Day Period.\nNEW ORLEANS. La.. Oct' 13.\nGov. J. 'M. .Parker of Louisiana will\nissue a proclamation Monday catling\non every cotton ginner in tha state\nto close his plant until the distressed\ncotton market is relieved and tha\nprice ot the staple once more ap\nproaches the production cost.\nIn addition to issuing this proc\nlamation Gov. Parker will at the same\ntime address a message to the gov\nernor of every other state in the cot\nton belt requesting them to take\nimilar action \"in order that the cot\nton industry may be saved from vic\ntual annihilation.\" -The\naction of the governor is ex\npected to crystalline the organization\nplaws already 'launched by the touisl\nna division of the American Cotton\nassociation, under the direction. of\ntV\". B. Thompson chtirmSn of the di\nvision. Mt. Thompson already has d\ndfessei letters 19 ginners of the\nCouth expressing the plan to them in\ndetail and asking every in owner\nto close his plant for 30 days, be\nginning Nov. 1, declaring the only\nWay to Overcome the present low\nprices is to prevent jthe unginned cot\nton from becoming marketable by to\nfusing to gin it\nMessages received by local cotton\ntnen from various sections of the\nSouth indicate that the movement to\nclose the gins is proving popular and\nthat in many cases the ginners them\nselves will take the initiative by fol\nlowing the suggestions to close.\nWAR EXHIBIT PROVES\nHIT AT JACKSON FAIR\nJACKSON, Miss., Oct. 23. With\nthe opening of the Mississippi state\nfair in Jackson comes some interest\ning exhibits, especially the military\nexhibits. At the entrance of the fair\ngrounds two large flags are displayed\nby the local army recruiting station,\nwhich Invites all who enter to view\none of the best free exhibits that can\nbe seen in the fairgrounds. There\nare many interesting war relics cap\ntured by the American soldiers.\nA large hospital tent has been\npitched and there is always world\nwar veterans on hand to answer all\nquestions that young men and their\nparents may ask. Tho tent is dec\norated with flags and bunting and\nfilled with all kinds of relics. Sergt.\nHarry E. Weintraub, from the Elev\nenth infantry (Mississippi's own reg\niment), who is a splendid specimen\nof American doughboy, Is in charge\nof the tent and has made many\nfriends since the f air has, started.\nSergt. Weintraub is one of the Elev\nenth infantry athletes who has won\nmany boxing exhibitions throughout\nthe country and abroad, and is Just\nas good a friend winner because of\nthe broad smile that the sergeant\nconstantly wears.\nAmong the army officers who vis\nited the display on Tuesday was Col,\nW. R. Sample, inspector instructor\nof the Third inspection district, with\nheadquarters at Atlanta, Oa. I Col.\nSample was accompanied by MaJ. H\nO. Olson, Mississippi district recruitr\ning officer, dpt. Thorn tan Chase,\nexecutive officer; First Lieut John\nF. Somors, assistant recruiting offi\ncer, and Sergts. Cline. and Wein\ntraub. In the evening a display of\narmy signal lights such as was used\nin the world war helped to illuminate\nthe fairgrounds. A similar display\nwill be in progress each night in\nfront of the army tent.\nTHREEliSWLAST\nIN MILL AT MOSSVILLE\nLAUREL, Miss, odt. 23. Two per\nsons, one white and one negro, were\nkilled as a result of an explosion of\na boiler at the mill ot the Tallahoma\nLumber company, at Mossvillo,\nThursday, night, and a third, a negro\nboy, 14, died yesterday morning in\nthe hospital here from injuries re\nceived in the explosion. A score era\nployed at the plant suffered minor\ninjuries. One man is in the Laurel\nGeneral hospital, badly injured.\nThe injured men sufferd from fly\ning debris and timbers, the whole\nmill being wrecked.\nThe dead are: John Barnett, Lu\ncius Sims and Sam Lindsey.\nThe explosion occurred at quitting\ntime. Barnett had Just started to\nblow the whistle when the explosion\noccurred. His body was thrown 60\nfeet and fell on top of a lumber pile.\nLumber stacked on the place was\nblown hundreds of feet by the force\nor the explosion.\nPADUCAH. Ky. Mrs. Mary E Mor\ngan, a resident of Paducah all of hr\nlife, died at her home. Mrs. Morgan\nwas well knowiV In Psducsh. She Is\nsurvived by two daughters, Miss hmrnn\nMorgan and Mrs. W. J. Rye, of I'a\nducah, and two sons. Robert I Mor\ngan, of Paducah. and George T. Mor\ngan, Tampji, Kla.\nPINE BLUFF, Ark. Mr Alva E.\nBrown, aged 52, wife of C O. Brown,\nplanter of Cornrsvllle. Llnooln county,\ndied here., Besides her husband, she is\nsurvived by three sons. Will Free, of\nYorktown; Jim Free, of Cornersville,\nand Travis Brown, of Cornersville;\nthree daughters. Mrs. Louise Mile, of\nCornersville; Mrs. Alvln fullbright. cf\nYorktown, and Miss Ethe Brown, of\nCornersville.\nflNE BLUFF. Art. Capt. J. H.\nDrosta, aged 88, of aeffersonviils. Ind.,\ndied here at the home of his daughter,\nMrs. W. C. Wood. Besides his widow,\nhe Is survived by four daughters. Mrs.\nWood and Mrs. Chas. B. Baker, of\nTim Bluff; Mrs. Chas. Ciller, of Mans\nfield, La., and Mrs. a tit tacey. f\nJeffersonvllle, And.\nHTJNTSVILLE, Ala. t. Heno towe,\nof Hazle Green, one of the oldest resi\ndents of that section of Madison county,\ndied at his home in that village after,\na long Illness. Ha was 77 year old.\nHe leaves eight children,-four sons and\nfour daughters.- The sons are C. S.,\nJ. D. And -I. H. Lowe. Jr., of Kal\nGreen, und Robert F. Lowe, of Hunts\nville, and' tha daughters are Mrs. Base\nSimmons, of Montgomery, Mrs. J. S.\nThompson, of Nashville: Mrs. B.\nFudge, of Memphis, ane) Mrs, 0. Js.\nGraham, of Have Green.\nHlTSTfiT,. Tenik wuneral ervlcs\nfor Frank Beckner. Norfolk ft Western i\nrailway fireman, who was Killed in a\nwreck near Rural atetreat. Va.. were\nheld at the Mary Street Methodist\nchurch. Rev. W. C. Thompson, oftlcl-!\nated.. Burial was la East Hill ceme\ntery.\nRRTRTOT.. Tenn. Funeral service\nover the Body of Earl B. Smith, who\ndied suddenly Tuesday ;1at Greenville,\nS. C were held here rnursaay a mo\nFirst Baptist church, Rev. J. L. Ros\nser, pastor of ths church, officiating.\nHo was 43 years old and is survived\nbv his widow, one Bon, Glenn fimlth.\nand one brother, R. H. Smith, ef this\ncity.\n1\nRRTSTOT Term. G. A. tne. aged\n61, died at the residence of Mrs. C.\nI Dunn, on Moore street. Burviving\nhim are two daughters,, and one son.\nTUEZlflVANT. Tenn. Mrs. Lucy\nSpringer died at her home in Atwood,\nthis county. She was 60 years old and\nmember., or the uumDerianu errauj-\nterian church. She Is survived by her\nhusband, Wallace Springer, and two\nsons, Dennis and Guy Springer.\nPADUCAH, Ky. Following an op-\neration for appendicitis. Claude Rog\ners. !0. a car repairer at the Illinois\nCentral railroad shops, died here at\nRiverside hospital. Ho is survived oy\nhis widow and three children, Margaret,\nTHREE STILLS RAIDED\nBY PADUCAH OFFICERS\nPADUOAH, Ky., Oct 23. Three\nraids conducted here by federal pro\nhibition agents resulted in the con\nfiscation of three stills and four gal\nlons of white corn whisky. A copper\nBtill of 80-gallon capacity, the largest\nthat has been found in Paducah, wan\nseized in a raid at the home of\nOorgo Woods. Two gallons of\n\"moonshine\" were captured at the\nsoft drink stand of John H. Elrod,\nand two stills, together with a quan\ntity of illicit liquor were taken in a\nraid, on tho home of Robert Massey.\nAll confiscated properties were re\nmoved to the federal building.\n.On churge of violating the Mann\nact, Thomas Jalmenro, an Italian and\nex-soldier, is held in the McCracken\ncounty Jail to appear before the fed\neral grand Jury here in- November.\nJalmenro was returned to Paducah\nfrom Louisville Wednesday by Dep\nuty United Stales Marshal R.W. Kim\nbell. He was arrested by Chicago\nauthorities in connection with his al\nleged elopement with Miss Galena\nHoward, 16, of Calvert City. Ky.\nfrissffcJ\nMai. New\nT11T We On aid \"Owl\nft a fk Os R yovr battery\ni f f 1 mM\nyy I en\nv m aw\nWH'H'Mtot UlMB M Lb.\nSPRINKLING HOSE\n60 -ft. Guaranteed Hose, Including\nCouplings and Nozzle\n$8.50\"$ 1 1. 50\"$ 1 2,50\nDelivered at Your Retldence\nIn City.\nTOWNER A CO., Inc.\nCorner Second and Union\nBurklngham-Parham Co.\nINSURANCE)\nM. 121. 1014 Exchange BWg.\nWITH OUR VISITORS\nMabel and Lucille Rogers.,\nPADUCAH. Ky. George Thomas\nDean. 2S, dted suddenly here. Surviv\ning are his widow and several children.\nRIPLEY. Miss. Miss Opal Randolph,\nl-vear-old daughter of Mr. and Mrs.\nJack Randolph, of the Pleasant Ridge\ncommunity, died at New Albany.\nEra Of Business\nDepression Before\nUs, Visitor Says\n'There is great need for the closest\nefficiency and economy for the nest\nfew years,', is the opinion of C. C.\nMatthewson, retired banker of Cano\nJaharie, N. Y.. now at Hotel Chtsca.\nwe have been drunk on prosperity\nand the period ot awakening is close\nat hand and the after effects are\ngoing to be bitter indeed.\n\"Another bad feature ie that Amer\nicans have grown to rely upon the\ngovernment to do everything. They\nforget that prosperity and failure rest\nentirely within ourselves and not In\nman-made laws. We, as a nation,\nhave grown to think that all we need\nto insure continued prosperity is to\npass a law .In favor of It. This at-\nititude would; be amusing if it were\nrmt fraught wit such danger to the\nnation,\nTh incoming atfmtnlstrattwi,\nwhehef Republican or Democratic,\nwill have no bed of rosed. We have\nperiod f great tiatlonaj stress tie\nfore us, and the fieoplc, i lnslcaA (if\nexalhlning tfiemselves, are going t\nclamor of government help. This\nadministration will get all the Mame\ntog strikes, lockouts, unemployment\nand other ills that always attend, an\nera cf business depression.\nMemphis Water 1\nRanks Very High,\nExpert Declares\n\"The health of a dry hangs more\non a liberal and pure supply of water\nthan any other one eingle considera\ntion, stated L I Millgram, form\nerly connected with, the United States\ngeological survey, now at the Pea-\nbody hotel, en route to South Amer\nica. \"Memphis is Very fortunate in\nthis as its water supply is such that\nany city would be proud to pos\nsess It,\n\"There is, It is true, considerable\niron in the water, but this is ex\ntremely advantageous as it is in\nJust about the right proportion for\nthe human system to absorb. Tho\nwater of Washington, L. C, is very\npoor; that of Kansas City is also\nwretched, especially when the (Mis\nsouri gets on a rampage, as it does\nwhen the spring freshets occur and,\nlater on in the summer, when the\nJuno rise comes. Then the water .is\nfilled with sand and mud and is re\npulsive to look upon and worse to\nthe taste.\nI do not mean that the water Is\nfilled with impurities, it is not; it is\nJust the sand from the river. There\nIs a class mat Deneve we snoum\nhave a certain percentage of sand\nthe grain, I mean in our systems.\nSuch persons should live in Kansas\nT\nPADUCAH, Ky. Announcement Is\nmade of the marriage of Miss Rosa\nMay Earles. daughter of Mr. and Mrs.\nA. J. Earles. to Morris HarriB Joiner,\nwhich took place in Paris. Tenn. Mr.\nand Mrs. Jeiucr will make their home\nin paducah.\nPINE BLUFF. Ark. Miss ForreBt\nJohnson and Joe ureshaM were mar\nried at Beech Street Baptist church\nby the Rev. J. E. Merrill, who per\nformed the ring ceremony. The bride Is\nthe daughter of Joe Johnson and was\nreared In Fine Bluff, fl'he bridegroom\nis a young business man of this oily,\nand the couple will make their home\nin Fine lull.\nPINE BLUFF, Ark. Miss Vernon\nDoty, daughter of Mr. and Mrs. K. M,\nDoty, of this city, and James Garland\nAieaa were married by the Kev. J. K.\nMerrill, pastor of Beech Street Baptist\ncnurcn. ine Driae was a teacher in\nthe public schools and the bridegroom\nis an employe of the Cotton Belt rail\nway and makes Memphis his home,\nwhere the couple will live.\n\"My Feet and Hands Would\nS well Until I Couldn't Use\nThem'.' Rheumatism.\nFolks, if you suffer with rheuma\ntism, aching joints, lumbaero or neu\nralgia, read what Mr. Joseph Clakin,\noi jvaaoaa, mo., nas to say:\n\"I feel it is nv dutv to tell vnn oil\nsurrering with rheumatism what\nKirk's Kheumatic Remedy did for\nme. I suffered with rheumatism for\nyears and at times my feet and hands\nwuuiu swell unui i could not use\nthem. I had tried so many rheuma\ntism medicines and none seemed to\nneip me. One day I noticed an ad\nvertisement of Kirk's Rheumatic\nRemedy, and a friend of mine advised\nme to try it, after telling me of the\nwonderful results that she had gotten.\nI decided to. get a bottle and try it.\nAfter using one bottle, I felt like a\nnew person. I owe ft all to Kirk's\nKheumatic Remedy.\"\nDruggists and other dealers are\nauthorized to sell you Kirk's Rheu\nmatic Remedy on a positive money\nDacK guarantee. Buy, one bottle,\ntake it according to directions. You\nwill surely get relief. If hot you\ncan nave your money back.\nThis same guarantee applies to\nKirk's Vigortone, a fine tonic, Kirk's\nCough Syrup Kirk's Chill Tonic,\nKirk's Sarsaparilla Blood Purifier\nand Kirk's Liniment, made by Kirk's\ncnemicai t;o Memphis, Tenn. Isold\nby druggists everywhere. adv.\nTRUSTEE'S SALE.\nDefault having been made in the pay\nment of the debts and obligations\nsecured to De paid In a certain\ndeed of trust executed be 27th\nday of May, 1919, by Lillian Lan\ndry Nee v and husband. E. Austin\nNeely, to the undersigned as trustee, as\nsame appears of record In the office of\nthe register or Phelhy county. Tennes\nsee, in book 706, page 283, and the own\ner of the debt secured having reaueated\nthe undersigned to advertise and sell\nthe property secured by said deed of\ntrust, all of said Indebtedness having\nmatured by default in the payment of\na part thereof, at the option of the\nowner, this is to give notice that we\nwill, on\nMONDAY, NOVEMBER 8, 1920,\ncommencing at 12 o'clock noon, at the\nsouthwest corner of the courthouse,\nMemphis, Shelby county, Tennessee,\nand at the Adams avenue entrance\nthereof, proceed to sell at public outcry\nto the highest and best bidder for cash,\nthe following described, property to\nwit: Situated In Shelby county. Tennessee,\nas follows:\nIn the city of Memphis, lot No. S of\nWest Hlgbee Heights subdivision, as\nshown by plat of record In plat book B,\npage 128, of the register's office of\nShelby county, Tennessee, more par\nticularly described as follows: Begin\nning in the north line of Hlgbee avenue\none hundred twenty (120) tret west of\nthe west line of South' Rembert street;\nthence west with the north line of Hlg\nbee avenue fifty (60) feet; thence north\nand parallel with South Rembert street\none hundred and forty (140) feet to an\nalley; thence east with the soutn line\nof said alley fifty (50) feet; thence\nsouth parallel with South Rembert\nfstreet one hundred and forty (H0) feet\nto the point or Deginning.\nAll right and equity of redemption,\nhomestead and dower waived In said\ndeed of trust, and the title Is believed\nto be good, but we will sell and convey\nonly a trustee.\nBANK OF COMMERCE TRUST CO.\nTruster.\nBy S. J. SHEPHERD, Trust Officer.\nThis October II, 1920.\nCity.' They would have it whenever\nthey took a drink. What I have said\nabout Kansas City refers to all the\nriver towns, Leavenworth, Atchison,\nOmaha, Council Bluffs and others.\nMissouri water is so thick that when\never the housewife finds her soup\nor sauce too thin she thickens it 'Ut\na little water from the river.\nrapidity as the tenant farmer. Some\nthing 'should be done to check this\nor the nation will suffer, In fact la\nsuffering now.\nSpeaker Deplores\nHegira From Farms\nIn New England\n\"The drift from farm to aities is\nappalling, especially In New Eng\nland.\" stated C. D. Kmling. of\nChessman, Vt horse breeder, now at\nHotel (eayoao. One will pass farm\nafter farm with -the windows of the\nformer home boarded up and the sign\n'for sale' to be seen. Our people\nleave for Boston and the West,' or\nease to Montreal, and they are then\nlost to us forever.\n\"This is a problem that grows In\nimmensity and one that should have\nthe most earnest consideration of our\nstatesmen, but. so far they have done\naospiuteiy nothing. From what I\nhao seen in my travels and heard\nfront others, this condition is general\nall ever the country. In New York\nrural districts and in some of tho\nbest .districts in the state at that\none will pass farnt after farm that is\ngiven up to weeds and neglect. The\ncountry can not flourish when It la\ndying in the heart.\n\"I do not think thai the condition\nI speak of is as bad in the South as\nelsewhere, but, unless something is\ndone. It will not be long before your\ncotton plantations are as deftnlate\nas the farms and orchards of New\nEngland and New York. Tenant\nfarming is blamed for much of this.\nbut that does not cover the ground\nruliy, for in my state tho owners of\nfarms are leaving with the\nDIDN'T KNOW\n'TWAS SO GOOD\nTexas Lady Storekeeper, Who\nCarries Black-Draught in\nStock, Has Found It\n\"Best Liver Medicine\"\nObtainable.\nBarker, Texas. Relating her (experi\nence with Thedford's Black-Draught,\nMrs. A. L F-omme, of this place, says:\n'!I had for some time used and\nother llvor medicines, which would\nnauseate and make me feel bad. We\nhave a store, and our customers called\nfor Black-Draught so often I decided\nIt must be good, so thought I would\ntry it myself.\n\"I began Its use and found It just\nfitted my case. It neither griped nor\nnauseated me, was an easy laxative\nand not hard to take. i\n\"I had had headaches a great deal\nno doubt from torpid liver. The Black-\nDraught would cure them. The best\nway I find to take Black-Draught Is to\ntake one or two good sized doses until\nthe liver begins to 'actj. then taper the\ndoses'to just a pinch after meals.\n\"It will Insure good digestion, do\naway with the gas or bad taste In the\nmouth, and is without doubt the best\nliver medicine In the market. I have\nfound it so. I can recommend It to my\nfriends, for I believe It will do them\ngood.\"\nGet a package of Thedford's Black-\nDraught liver medicine today.\nMost dealers carry It in stock. adv,\nTRUSTEE'S SALE.\nDefault having been made In the\npayment of the debts and obligations\nsecured to be paid in a certain deed of\ntrust, executed the 2th day of October,\n1915, by Benjamin F. Hammond, Jr.,\nand wife. Edith M. Hammond, to the\nundersigned as trustee, as same ap\npears of record In the office of the\nregister ot Shelby County. Tennessee,\nin Book fitt. Pare 86. and the owner\nof the debt secured having requested\nthe undersigned to advertise and sell\nthe property secured by said deed of\ntrust, all of said indebtedness having\nmatured by default In the payment of\na part thereof, at the option of tho\nowner this is to give notice, tliut I\nwill, on\nMONDAY. NOVEMBER 8. 1920,\ncommencing at 12 o'clock noon, at the\nsouthwest corner of tho courthouse,\nMemphis, Shelby County, Tennessee,\nand at the Adams avenue entrance\nthereof, proceed to. sell at public out\ncry to the highest and best bidder for\ncash, the following described property,\nto-wit:\nSituated in Memphis, Shelby County,\nTennessee, as follows:\nThe east fifty (50) feet of the west\none hundred (100) feet of the south\ntwo hundred (200) feet; and the north\nforty (40) feet of the south two hun\ndred (200) feet of the west fifty (50)\nfeet of Lot No. 4. Block B2, South\nMemphis, described ns follows:\nBeginning at a point In the north\nline of Linden avenue. !02.12 feet east\nof the intersection or the north line\nof Linden avenue, with the east line\nof South Wellington street: running\nthence eaut with the north lino of Lin\nden avenue fifty (50) feet; thence\nnorth parallel with South Wellington\nstreet two hundred (200) feet; thence\nwest parallel with Linden avenue 100\nfeet; thence south parallel with South\nWellington street 40 feet: thence east\nparallel with Linden avenue 50 f-et;\nthence south parallel with South Well\nington street 160 feet to the north line\nof Linden avenue, the point of be\nginning, belntr those two parcels of\nground conveyed to Mary J. Morlarty\nbv deeds of record In Book 400. Page\nfi39. and Book 400. Page 535. respec\ntively, of the register's office of Shelby\nCounty. Tennessee, and being the same\nproperty conveyed to B. F. Hammond,\nJr., by Mary J. Morlarty and husband.\nJohn H. Morlarty, by warranty deed\ndated October 25, 1015.\nAll right and equity of redemption,\nhomestead and dower waived In said\ndeed of trust, and the title is believed\nto be eoihI. but 1 will sell and convey\nonlv as trustee,\nPKTKK (i. GRANT, Trustee.\nThis October 1520.\nBOB MORAN LOSES\nHIS NIGHTSHIRT\nlost, somewhere between Mem\nphis and New Orleans or in the lat\nter city a perfectly good nightshirt:\nHob Moran. city electrician, who\nreturned Friday lnirht from a con\nvention In New Orleans declared Sat.\nurday that ho had sustained his rec\nord on his latest trip and was seri\nously considering the Insertion of an\nadvertisement for the missing nightie.\nMoran says that every time he\nmakes a trip he loses a nightie and\nhe had fond hope) of breaking the\n'reccrd this time, but upon his return\n.heme late Friday discovered that he\nhail run true Tu form and was lack\nlng a new nightshirt that had been\noccupied onii' a couple of times.\nWAR DEFICIT SHOWN.\nROMK, Oct. 23. Official fltures are\nDow publish) showing that from Aug-\nUKt 1. 1914, to June 30. 1920, Italy spent\n110.700.000,000 lira in connection wtin\nthe war, while the Income during the\nsame period amounted to only S9.000.\n000,000 lira. These expenditures Include\nthe normal sums for running tn